<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 6:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2741d4f0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>6.</label.designator><headtext>Judicial Notice of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7af2682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>6:4.</label.designator><headtext>Law—Statutes</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-2-220" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0abf29907fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-2-220</cite.query>, the Georgia courts will take judicial <page no="161"/>notice of all public acts of the General Assembly of Georgia and of the United States[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3602d507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] as well as the legislative journals of the Georgia General Assembly.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic36054607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] In the past, when considering a constitutional question about an act of the General Assembly, a court would not take judicial notice of a statute with a notation of “as amended” or referenced by an unofficial citation.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic36054617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] However, the Georgia Supreme Court overruled several cases to change this rule in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1980193591" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0ac0fe527fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Grantham v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic36054627fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] and extended Grantham in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1982119911" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0ac1e8b27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Wiggins v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic36054637fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] by holding that the court will consider a constitutional challenge where the statutory provision attacked is identified “with fair precision,” even without a citation.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic3602d507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1954105310" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0abf77b27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Heard v. Pittard, 210 Ga. 549, 81 S.E.2d 799 (1954)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1960123540" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0abf77b57fc011ea988285db8533e975">R. G. Foster &amp; Co. v. Fountain, 216 Ga. 113, 114 S.E.2d 863 (1960)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1947103800" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0abf77b87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Crowley v. Hughes, 74 Ga. App. 531, 40 S.E.2d 570 (1946)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic36054607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1959123911" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0abfece27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Sharpe v. Lowe, 214 Ga. 513, 106 S.E.2d 28 (1958)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1963126134" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0abfece57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Atlanta Metallic Casket Co. v. Mosby Truck Service, Inc., 107 Ga. App. 677, 131 S.E.2d 590 (1963)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic36054617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1960123052" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0ac062127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Adams v. Ray, 215 Ga. 656, 113 S.E.2d 100 (1960)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic36054627fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1980193591" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0ac125627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Grantham v. State, 244 Ga. 775, 262 S.E.2d 777 (1979)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic36054637fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017100" w-serial-number="1982119911" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0ac20fc27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Wiggins v. State, 249 Ga. 302, 290 S.E.2d 427 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 6:4<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
